<dl id="n12085d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12085d">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12085d"> 85(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ <font face="wake">H</font> decorations</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>A German Town</b> But the Opera-house in the town <font color="green">[of Bayreuth]</font> is as remarkable as the Wagnerian one, and much pleasanter to look at <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Designed by Giuseppe <mark>Bibbiena</mark>, no more perfect example of the eighteenth-century opera-house is to be found anywhere&mdash;not even in Italy, the home of the theatre. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The fa&ccedil;ade <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> is merely like the heavy leather case for the intricate, fantastic piece of jewelry; for the interior is <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> more beautiful even than the Ph&oelig;nix at Venice or the San Carlo at Naples. Like these, <mark>the theatre is built up entirely out of opera-boxes</mark> <small> <a name="CRII" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CRII"><cite title="source">The Criterion</cite></a>, II, VIII (July 1924)</cite></a> 444-5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
